> When we first started HelloFresh, we used to get all sorts of emails from people
> saying that they were 'scared' of fish. Whether Steven Spielberg related, or
> something to do with it welding to their frying pan, we soon knocked their phobia
> into touch with a few easy recipes. Next on our scary-food-hitlist is duck - far
> more simple than you might believe! Our tip here is to leave the duck out of the
> fridge for 30 mins before you cook it, so it cooks evenly.

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees and season the @duck breasts{2} with @salt{}
and @pepper{}. Cut three slices across the duck skin with a sharp #knife{} and
lay in a cold #griddle pan{} skin-side down (just use a #frying pan{} if you don't
have a griddle pan). Cook on medium-low heat for about ~{8%minutes} or until the
fat is crisp and golden. Transfer to a #baking dish{} skin-side up and cook for
~{10-15%minutes} on the top shelf of the oven.

Finely dice the @red chilli{1} (we used 1 tbsp for a warm little kick). Peel and
very, very finely dice the @carrot{1}(peeled and finely diced 5mm cubes) (5mm cubes
if your skills allow!). Peel and core the @Cox's apple{1} before chopping into
1cm cubes. Peel and finely dice your @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely diced).
Cut your @spring greens{1/2}(sliced and tough root discarded) leaves into roughly
1cm slices, discard the tough root.

Melt @?butter{1%tbsp} (if you have some) in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-low
heat. Tip: If you don't have any butter, use ½ tbsp of olive oil. Toss in the
apple, @?sugar{1%tsp} (if you have it) and @water{3%tbsp} and place a #lid{} on
the pan. Allow to cook for ~{10%minutes} until the apple has softened up. Tip:
Remove the lid to thicken the apple sauce in the last few mins. When the 10 mins
are up, take the pan off the heat.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a frying pan on medium heat. Gently fry the chilli,
carrot and shallot for ~{5%minutes}. Drain and thoroughly rinse the @organic lentils{1}
before adding to the pan, together with @vegetable stock pot{1/2} and
@water{75%ml}.

After ~{3%minutes}, take the lentils off the heat. Cover with a lid and leave
until it's time to serve.

Once the duck is cooked, take it from the oven and leave it to rest for
~{3%minutes}. Tip: We like our duck slightly pink in the middle but you can cook
it through if you like. Tip: Leaving meat to rest on a warm plate, allows the juices
to redistribute throughout the meat, leaving every mouthful nice and juicy.

Pour any excess fat from the duck into a frying pan and place on high heat. Once
hot, add the spring greens along with @salt{1/4%tsp} and a good grind of
@pepper{}. Fry for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Finely chop your @flat leaf parsley{3}(chopped) and stir it through the lentils.
Serve the duck on top of the lentils with a healthy dollop of your caramelised
apples. Serve with spring greens and savour!